  "prompt": "Why are Blonde Mongolia rare in America?",
  "response": "Blonde Mongolia are rare in America because they are not a native plant to the region. Blonde Mongolia, or *Magnolia denudata*, is originally from China, specifically in the temperate regions and is widely cultivated for its striking yellow flowers. The conditions required for this plant to thrive - specific soil types, climate, and overall care - may not be commonly met across the varied climates of the United States. This rarity is also compounded by the limited commercial availability and selective cultivation practices. Most regional nurseries and garden centers might not carry Blonde Mongolia due to its specialized needs and lack of widespread popularity compared to native or more commonly adapted species.",
